SIMPLE: mead
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mead
<hw>Mead</hw> <pr>(m⟦emac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>mede</ets>, AS. <ets>meodo</ets>; akin to D. <ets>mede</ets>, G.
<ets>met</ets>, <ets>meth</ets>, OHG. <ets>metu</ets>, <ets>mitu</ets>,
Icel. <ets>mj⟦oum⟧⟦edh⟧r</ets>, Dan. <ets>mi⟦oum⟧d</ets>, Sw.
<ets>mj⟦oum⟧d</ets>, Russ. <ets>med'</ets>, Lith. <ets>midus</ets>, W.
<ets>medd</ets>, Gr. <grk>me`qy</grk> wine, Skr. <ets>madhu</ets> honey,
a sweet drink, as adj., sweet. ⟦root⟧270. Cf. <er>Metheglin</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A fermented drink made of water and honey with malt,
yeast, etc.; metheglin; hydromel.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A drink composed of sirup of sarsaparilla or other
flavoring extract, and water. It is sometimes charged with carbonic acid
gas.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mead</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mead
<hw>Mead</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m⟦aemac⟧d</ets>. See
<er>Meadow</er>.]</ety> <def>A meadow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>mede</qex>⟦br⟧
All full of freshe flowers, white and reede.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To fertile vales and dewy <qex>meads</qex>⟦br⟧
My weary, wandering steps he leads.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meadow</ent>⟦br⟧
